==Music video==
[[Image:GarbageVowvideo.JPG|thumb|right|The "Vow" music video marked the first time Garbage performed together live, and the band liked the experience enough to start touring.|alt=A female singer and a male bassist and drummer perform against a golden backdrop.]]
The music video for "Vow" was directed by [[Samuel Bayer]] and filmed over 12 hours in [[Los Angeles]]<ref name="musician"/> at the start of June 1995.<ref name=ModAge>{{cite journal|last=Boehler|first=Eric|title=The Modern Age|date=1996-06-17|journal=Billboard|pages=85|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8AsEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA85&dq=Garbage%20Vow&pg=PA85#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> The video premiered in the United States on June 12, 1995.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vow / Samuel Bayer.|url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=20&ti=1,20&Search_Arg=Bayer%2C%20Samuel&Search_Code=NALL&CNT=25&PID=xA-todi9cOxmdvQ7fjWR5LbS2c9V&SEQ=20111202153821&SID=3|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|accessdate=2011-07-27|date=1995-06-12|quote=PA0000704797; Vow / Samuel Bayer; Videocassette; 3/4 in; Music video performed by Garbage; Almo Sounds, Inc.}}</ref>  

A performance piece, the video features [[strobe light]]ing and falling [[glitter]] cut into shots of Garbage performing against a golden backdrop surrounded by television sets relaying real time footage of the band playing. Throughout the clip there is also shots of a semi-naked man with running black [[eyeliner]] crawling on the floor.<ref>{{cite video|people= |date = 1995-06-12|title= Vow: Music Video |medium= DVD |publisher =Almo Sounds, Inc}}</ref>

Bayer asked the group to perform "Vow" live while he filmed the takes for the video shoot.<ref name=Serendipitous/> Garbage had never performed live as group prior to this, and had initially had not considered ever performing live onstage.<ref name="musician"/> "We set up amps and played guitars. Butch was pounding away and Shirley had a live mic. After the first run-through, we all looked at each other and said, 'This feels really good.'" Erikson later recalled.<ref name="musician"/> The group enjoyed the experience so much that they quickly changed their minds, and scheduled [[Garbage tour|tourdates later that year]].<ref name=Serendipitous/>

The "Vow" music video was first commercially released on [[VHS]] and [[Video-CD]] on 1996's ''[[Garbage Video]]''.<ref name="GarbageVideo">{{cite journal|title=The Screens Are Full of Garbage|journal=[[Melody Maker]]|location=UK|date=1996-12-07}}</ref> A remastered version was later included on Garbage's 2007 greatest hits [[DVD]] ''[[Absolute Garbage#Absolute Garbage DVD|Absolute Garbage]]''.<ref name="absolutegarbage">{{cite web|url=http://www.garbage.com/news/news.php?id=118| title=New Best Of Album|publisher=Garbage.com|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090620204305/http://www.garbage.com/news/news.php?uid=336|archivedate=2009-06-20|accessdate=2011-07-22}}</ref>

==Critical reception==
Upon its release, "Vow" received a positive response from music critics. ''[[The Times]]'' described it as "the missing link between [[Courtney Love]] and [[PJ Harvey]]"<ref>{{cite news|title=Album Reviews|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=1995-09-19}}</ref> while Paul Yates of ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine said "Garbage's signature lies in songs like 'Vow', good pop tunes dealt a rough treatment and brazen vocals".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Albums: ''Garbage''|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|date=1995-11-01|first=Paul|last=Yates}}</ref> ''NME'''s Emma Morgan wrote "it's the simplicity of the lyrics that strikes the winning goal",<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[NME]]|first=Emma|last=Morgan|title=Natty Dregs|date=1995-09-23}}</ref> while earlier in the year ''NME'' had made "Vow" its Single of the Week,  writing "["Vow" is] a shape-shifting squalling epic. It shimmers like [[Siouxsie Sioux|Siouxsie]]'s '[[Christine (song)|Christine]]'. It's a credit to the band's producing skills that such an ambitious thing is lashed together at all"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[NME]]|title=''Vow'' Single of the week|date=1995-03-25}}</ref> ''Melody Maker'' also named "Vow" as Single of the Week, describing the song as "surreal pop heaven mixed with industrial nightmares".<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Melody Maker]]|title="Vow" Single of the Week|date=1995-03-11}}</ref>
and later saying the song "has classic written all over it".<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Melody Maker]]|title=Singles of The Year|date=1995-12-09}}</ref> ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine's Paul Rees described "Vow" as "edgy dislocated pop with a sparkling chorus"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Kerrang!]]|first=Paul|last=Harrison|title=Singles; [[Subhuman (Garbage song)|Subhuman]]"|date=1995-08-05}}</ref> and "the most brilliant pop song of 1995".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Sweet, Litter and Twisted|publisher=[[Kerrang!]]|date=1995-09-29|first=Paul|last=Rees}}</ref> [[Select (magazine)|Select]]'s Ian Harrison liked the song, but felt that it "pilfers from [[The Smiths]] '[[How Soon Is Now?]]'".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Paul|last=Harrison|title=The Vig Time |journal=[[Select (magazine)|Select]]|date=1995-10-01}}</ref> In a review for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Larry Flick rated "Vow" his Critic's Choice and wrote, "Move over Courtney Love. Garbage combine the tough-headed hooks of [[Hole (band)|Hole]] with an unforgettable vocal prowl which rivals '[[Miss World (song)|Miss World]]'. A numbed female vocal cries before a raging guitar riff begins to shatter a pain-filled pop texture. Commit to it."<ref>{{cite journal|last=Flick|first=Larry|title=Singles Reviews|date=1995-07-15|journal=Billboard|pages=67|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ygsEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA67&dq=Garbage%20Vow&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Dan Dinello, of ''[[Alternative Press]]'', described "Vow" as "menacing tale of violence and revenge sounds like [[Patti Smith]] fronting [[The Clash]] while quoting the [[The Beatles|Beatles]] "[[No Reply (song)|No Reply]]"."<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dinello|first=Dan|title=Pop And All That Junk|url=http://www.garbage.net/articles/@alt.htm|journal=[[Alternative Press]]|accessdate=2011-07-20|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20010212093534/http://www.garbage.net/articles/@alt.htm|archivedate=2001-02-12|date=1995-12-01}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''{{'}}s Charles Aaron likened the band to "[[Echo and the Bunnymen|Bunnymen]] wannabes doing '90s reverb angst" and compared Erikson's guitar to [[Aldo Nova]], but ultimately considered that "even though they sound totally prefab, the singer hints at a pleasantly pissed personality".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Aaron|first=Charles|title=Singles|date=November 1995|journal=Spin|pages=131|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=EYlQ2Hsft8QC&pg=PA131}}</ref>

"Vow" also appeared in a number of year-end lists: #45 in John Peel's [[Festive Fifty]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/johnpeel/festive50s/1990s/1995/|title=Keeping It Peel: Festive 50's "1995"|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2008-02-05}}</ref> #15 in [[Triple J]]'s "[[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100 of 1995]]",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklists.com/jjj-1995.html|title=Triple J "Hottest 100 of 1995"|publisher=Rocklists.com|accessdate=2008-02-05}}</ref> and #66 in [[KROQ-FM|KROQ]]'s "Top 106.7 of 1995".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklists.com/kroq-1995.html|title=KROQ's "Top 106.7 of 1995|publisher= Rocklists.com|accessdate=2008-02-05}}</ref>

